    <html:p>Now, supposing that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {N}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> property, can we show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex> does as well?</html:p>
    <html:p>Here there are four possibilities to consider:
<html:ol><html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, or</html:li>
<html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex>, or</html:li>
<html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>, or</html:li>
<html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ol></html:p>
    <html:p>Let's look at each in turn:
<html:ol><html:li>if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, then since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> is a Dunn-Belnap valuation we know <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has the property, this means <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> too; and then since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex> is a strong Kleene valuation, we get <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>;</html:li>
<html:li>by similar reasoning, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>;</html:li>
<html:li>by similar reasoning, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>; and</html:li>
<html:li>by similar reasoning, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ol></html:p>
    <html:p>This checks out!
So indeed, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {N}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> property, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  A]]></fr:tex> does as well; this means that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg ]]></fr:tex> preserves this property.</html:p>
