            <fr:title text="Can we treat both \mathsf {\mathbf {B}} and \mathsf {\mathbf {N}} as \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}?">Can we treat both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>?</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>A third thing that we might think about is coming back the other way.
We've seen two different ways to get Dunn-Belnap valuations from a strong Kleene valuation.
But suppose we have a Dunn-Belnap valuation instead; can we use that to reach a strong Kleene valuation in a useful way?</html:p>
            <html:p>Spoiler: this is the idea I want to explore that <html:em>won't</html:em> work out, so that you can see up close what it looks like when this doesn't go smoothly.
This is important: when you're doing reasoning like this to explore a question, you can't know in advance how things will go.
That's why you're doing the reasoning: to find out!
We've seen two cases where it does work, but those are very special.
More usual would be a case like this, where it doesn't work.
Let's dive in!</html:p>
            <html:p>Suppose we begin from some Dunn-Belnap valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>, and we want to generate a strong Kleene valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>.
One natural thought, based roughly on what we've just looked at, might be to leave <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> as they are, and to treat both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>.
That is, let's think about the strong Kleene valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex> such that for all atomic sentences <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, we have:
<html:ul><html:li>if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(A) = v(A)]]></fr:tex>, and</html:li>
<html:li>if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ul></html:p>
            <html:p>Since valuations can do whatever they like with atomic sentences, there surely is such a strong Kleene valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>.
Again, it's handy to have a name for the property we're looking at, the one we set up for all atomic sentences, so that we can explore whether it applies to all sentences.
Let's call it the "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {N}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> property".</html:p>
            <html:p>So now we want to see whether all connectives preserve the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {N}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> property.</html:p>
