                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
                <html:p>Again, we want to show that whenever sentences <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> have the property, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \land  B]]></fr:tex> does as well.</html:p>
                <html:p>This time, assuming that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> have the property doesn't let us ignore any parts of these tables, though; we've got to consider all possibilities, since we're starting from any Dunn-Belnap valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>.
Instead, we want to think of what we're trying as like "smooshing" the two values <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex> down into the one value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>, while leaving <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> alone.
So you might even look at the Dunn-Belnap table here like this:</html:p>
                <html:table style="border-collapse: collapse;">
  <html:thead><html:tr>
    <html:td class="topedge leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land ]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge leftbord distinguish"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge rightbord distinguish"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  </html:tr></html:thead>
  <html:tbody>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="leftbord distinguish"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="rightbord distinguish"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge topbord distinguish"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="topbord distinguish"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="distinguish"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="rightbord distinguish"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge botbord distinguish"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="botbord distinguish"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="botbord distinguish"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td class="botbord rightbord distinguish"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
  </html:tbody>
</html:table>
                <html:p>But now we can see a problem.
Looking to the strong Kleene table, we can see three internal cells with the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>.
These are the values <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex> gives to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \land  B]]></fr:tex> when either <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> has the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>, and neither of them has the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>
That is, when either <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(B) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> and both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(A)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(B)]]></fr:tex> are not <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(A \land  B) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
                <html:p>Now look to the Dunn-Belnap table.
When <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A)]]></fr:tex> must be either <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>.
And similarly, when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(B) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(B)]]></fr:tex> must be either <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>.
(Remember, we're supposing that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> have the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {N}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> property.)
Similarly, if both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(A)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(B)]]></fr:tex> are not <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, then both <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(B)]]></fr:tex> must not be <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> either.
So we have eight possibilities to consider; these are the distinguished cells in the table.
</html:p>
                <html:p>For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \land  B]]></fr:tex> to have the property, we would need to see only <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex> in those distinguished cells.
But there are two <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>s in there!
This gives us the clue we need to show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land ]]></fr:tex> does <html:em>not</html:em> preserve the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {N}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> property.</html:p>
                <html:p>It's time to fill in a concrete case.
Suppose our initial Dunn-Belnap valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> is such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex>.
Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p \land  q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.
But the strong Kleene valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex> we've determined from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(p \land  q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>.
The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {N}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> property fails for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  q]]></fr:tex>.
But we set up <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex> so that the property would hold for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>; so we can see that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land ]]></fr:tex> does not preserve the property.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>28</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/005U/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>005U</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/005U/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="What does this show?">What does this show?</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>So, given a Dunn-Belnap valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>, we can indeed reach a strong Kleene valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex> as specified.
But this strong Kleene valuation is not related to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> in any particularly convenient way, at least as far as we've seen.
The attempt to extend the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {N}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> property from atomic sentences to all sentences has failed.</html:p>
                <html:p>Moreover, it's not just like we tried to show this and came up empty: we even found a particular Dunn-Belnap valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> where the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {N}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> property does not hold of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  q]]></fr:tex>.
So there's no point in continuing to try to show that this property holds of all sentences; we know it doesn't.</html:p>
                <html:p>Here's another way to look at what we've shown: given a Dunn-Belnap valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>, we might set up a function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex> from sentences to strong Kleene values that matches <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, and collapses both of the values <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {B}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {N}}]]></fr:tex> to the single value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>.
What we've just shown, though, is that this function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex> won't generally be a strong Kleene valuation!
It will match our strong Kleene valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex> on atomic sentences, but not on all sentences.
So there isn't much we could do with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex> to connect Dunn-Belnap valuations to the strong Kleene structure.</html:p>
                <html:p>Unfortunately, that doesn't really tell us much else.
Is our strong Kleene valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex> related to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> in some other way worth exploring?
For all I've said here, maybe it is and maybe it isn't.
Or is there some <html:em>other</html:em> way to take a Dunn-Belnap valuation and generate a strong Kleene valuation that's usefully related to it?
For all I've said here, maybe there is and maybe there isn't.</html:p>
                <html:p>That's just life, I'm afraid: it's nice when things work out, but it's not always so!</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
